ame><gtr:roles><gtr:role><gtr:name>PRINCIPAL_INVESTIGATOR</gtr:name></gtr:role><gtr:role><gtr:name>FELLOW</gtr:name></gtr:role></gtr:roles></gtr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE019269%2F1"><gtr:id>30BE289C-E3CB-4355-99BC-5DF38BEBC531</gtr:id><gtr:title>Off-shoring and Outsourcing Innovation? The New Challenge for Multinationals</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E019269/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Recent evidence suggests that multinational companies are now off-shoring their innovation activities, much as they off-shored their manufacturing activities in the two decades before. Moreover, firms are increasingly locating their innovation activities in emerging economies such as China and India, rather than in North America, Western Europe and Japan. Simultaneously, innovation is increasingly ?open?, with firms outsourcing innovation to local firms in triad or emerging markets. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>Despite the many opportunities, off-shoring innovation (locating it in foreign countries) and outsourcing it (doing it with other organisations) raise significant challenges for multinationals. Morale and learning in in-house or home research and development operations may suffer; cross-national operations may become overly complex, lowering the efficiency with which firms convert ideas into finished products; and exposing intellectual property to competitors may result in the capture of value by others. &lt;/p> 
&lt;p>In response, this research addresses the following questions:&lt;/p> 
&lt;ul> 
 &lt;li>What is the extent and nature of outsourced and off-shored innovation in the world?s largest multinational companies? &lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>How do these firms manage the challenges posed by such innovation across nations? &lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>What is the role in multinational innovation of firm-specific factors such as structure, strategy, and culture relative to country-specific factors such as regulation and legislation?&lt;/li>
&lt;/ul></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-08-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-07-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>100853</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication><gtr:id>299C70F7-BEE1-4042-921C-56C08694445B</gtr:id><gtr:title>Scaling up social businesses in developing markets</gtr:title><gtr:parentPublicationTitle>Journal of Cleaner Production</gtr:parentPublicationTitle><gtr:authors><gtr:author url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/person/93fd52443f7c77df3fad4724480ad9fc"><gtr:id>93fd52443f7c77df3fad4724480ad9fc</gtr:id><gtr:otherNames>Bocken N</gtr:otherNames></gtr:author></gtr:authors><gtr:date>2016-01-01</gtr:date><gtr:outcomeId>58c70ff2716748.99445328</gtr:outcomeId></gtr:publication></gtr:publications><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-331-27-0010</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E019269/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>7D5D2DB2-0A64-42AF-A644-5F541B832A29</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Economics</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5E9AA4EC-49E3-4D6A-B545-79DA07CE39E0</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Management &amp; Business Studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>F0322ED6-113F-4530